Published at 12:01AM, April 22 2013
Companies should decide at the start of their financial year what dividend they plan to pay and not set it later as “an afterthought”, one of London’s most successful institutional investors is urging.
Stuart Rhodes, who manages the £6 billion M&G Global Dividend Fund, wants more companies to decide on their dividend first and then plan other things around that.
“Excellent businesses are those that make their dividend decision at the start of the year,” he said.
